i>minier</i> ‘miner’ (see   Minier  ). This surname is very rare in France; in North America it may thus (also) be an altered form of some other similar (like-sounding) French surname, such as   Mignon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Moynihan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Patrick James, Donal, Eamon, Finbarr, Kieran, Niall.","Irish:","Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Muimhneacháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Muimhneachán</i>’, a diminutive of the byname <i>Muimhneach</i> ‘Munsterman’, i.e. someone belonging to the province of Munster. In Mayo this surname has sometimes been translated into English as   Munster  . There has been some confusion with   Monaghan  ."]}]},{"name":"Gronwy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name of uncertain derivation, borne in the <i>Mabinogi</i> by  Goronwy the Staunch , Lord of Penllyn. He became the lover of the flower-maiden Blodeuedd and murdered her husband  Lleu Llaw Gyffes , but Lleu was later restored to life and definitively dispatched Goronwy."],"variants":[{"name":"Gronw","meanings":["Variant of   Goronwy ."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gronwy ap Einion was born in 1270, in Glynllifon, Caernarfonshire, Wales, his father, Einion ap Ieuan, was 38 and his mother, Efa ferch Ieuan, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Generis Verch Gwyn. He died in 1331, in Llandwrog, Caernarfonshire, Wales, at the age of 61, and was buried in Llandwrog, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1270–1331":"1270–1331","1274–Male":"1274–Surnud","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1300–1352":"1300–1352","1232–Male":"1232–Surnud","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1300":"1300","1245":"1245","1331":"1331","1265":"1265","1232":"1232","1352":"1352","1274":"1274","1270":"1270","19 December 133